    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Welwyn Sunday Afternoon 6 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest W. I am in high happiness at being fairly off at last; with the poor dear Old Hen less fussy, fidgety &amp; fanciful, &amp; more cheerful than I could have hoped.</p>
      <p>We have arrived here about a quarter of an hour; having had a very easy &amp; delightful</p>
      <p>drive. I particularly enjoyed driving thro' Bracket (Lord Melbourne's) between this &amp; Hatfield; but I wished much for you. I have seldom seen a Park I admired so much. I think none except Melbury. The ground is beautifully hilly &amp; undulated; &amp; full of noble old trees, brakes, &amp; picturesque points of view. Tomorrow morning</p>
      <p>I am to go over to see the Hall itself, &amp; some of the walks. The Hall is something like that in Clandon Park; it is a fine old red brick compact square.</p>
      <p>I did not see any deer in the Park.-- My mother seemed to feel interest &amp; pleasure in re-visiting the place she knew so well in her Aunt Lady Melbourne's time.</p>
      <p>Tomorrow afternoon we</p>
      <p>are to go on to Eaton.</p>
      <p>It is proposed that on Tuesday or Weddy I should get some saddle- -horses, &amp; ride over to Cambridge, 17 miles from Eaton, to spend 2 or maybe 3 nights, to see your Sisters. The Hen is uncertain if she will be now up to the Cambridge excursion herself; &amp; besides is anxious to remain near the Jones's &amp; Achesons I believe; &amp; they would be company for her while</p>
      <p>I might be away.</p>
      <p>She is devising all kinds of agreeable plans for me, which is only too kind; but she will talk of "having so much to be "grateful to me for".--</p>
      <p>I believe that I do do her good; &amp; that [two words crossed out] my company is both pleasure &amp; advantage to her. I certainly seem to have a good deal of power in composing her mind, &amp; helping her to decide.</p>
      <p>In Town she would</p>
      <p>hear of no place to stop at but Hake's Hotel in Manchester Sqre; &amp; as she had the fancy, I think it did her good that it was gratified. I was quite her running footman, &amp; went all sorts of errands over the Town for her. This I know was a comfort &amp; help.</p>
      <p>She was in great agony last night at parting with Elizabeth; as in all probability she will not see her again;</p>
      <p>perhaps Alas never! Tho' I will hope not quite this either. But E's health is of very uncertain &amp; frail tenure I think. E-- had no idea she was wishing my Mother a real Good Bye. Perhaps this was best. At least my Mother wished it, &amp; fancied it so.</p>
      <p>As I wrote you word yesterday morning, I would not sleep at the Hotel. I do hate them. But I went up at nine</p>
      <p>this morning; &amp; was in great delight at finding the Hen had slept perfectly well &amp; was inclined to go. So I lost no time in ordering everything to be ready, &amp; managing it all for her; &amp; smoothing off all the doubts &amp; apprehensions on the subject.--</p>
      <p>I saw no one in Town, except Dr Locock, whom I saw first with the Hen yesterday; &amp; who kindly</p>
      <p>came &amp; sat with me an hour this morning. He enters very agreeably &amp; kindly into all one's plans &amp; feelings; &amp; has been of great comfort to the Hen. But he quite perceives the little defects in her which are so injurious to her health; &amp; has spoken to me about them.--</p>
      <p>I will not say more now. I am well, &amp; in excellent spirits, &amp; very happy.</p>
      <p>I much enjoy this little</p>
      <p>tour; &amp; think it will be very beneficial, as well as delightful to me.</p>
      <p>You had best still direct to St James' Sqre; as we are a little uncertain; &amp; I write directions daily to Sarah.</p>
    </div></body>
